      \field{abstract}{Using corpus-based methods inspired by recurrence quantiﬁcation analysis, we investigate the patterns that shape coordination in dialogue, in particular during the process of language acquisition. We show that the turn-by-turn temporal development of conversation is a key factor inﬂuencing when and how interlocutors match each other’s linguistic representations. Although there is continuity between child-adult and adult-adult dialogue with respect to alignment of semantic representations, our results show important differences regarding syntactic alignment in adjacent turns, with adults showing less cross-speaker syntactic matches than expected by chance.}
